To prove the given relationship

\[
|\psi(0)|^{2}=\frac{m}{2 \pi}\left\langle\frac{\mathrm{d}V}{\mathrm{d}r}\right\rangle-\frac{1}{2 \pi}\left\langle\frac{L^{2}}{r^{3}}\right\rangle,
\]

we start from the time-independent Schrödinger equation:

\[
\left(-\frac{1}{2m} \nabla^{2}+V(\mathbf{r})\right)\psi=E\psi.
\]

We multiply both sides of this equation by \( r^{-n-1} e^{-\alpha r} Y_{l}^{m}(\theta,\phi) \), where \(\alpha\) is some positive constant to be determined later.

The left-hand side becomes:
\begin{align*}
\int d\mathbf{r}\, &e^{\dagger}(r)Y_{l}^{\prime *}(\theta,\varphi) \\
&=\int d\mathbf{r}\,\left[ -\frac{1}{2m} \Delta + V(\mathbf{r}) \right] \psi^{*} (\mathbf{r}) \, r^{-n-1}e^{-\alpha r}Y_{l}^{m*}(\theta,\varphi).
\end{align*}

Using Green's theorem on the Laplacian term we get:
\begin{equation}
\lim_{\epsilon\rightarrow 0^{+}} \oint_{S_\epsilon} \left[\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r})\, \partial_r \left(e^{-\alpha r} r^{-n-1} Y_l^{m*} (\theta , \varphi ) \right)- \left\{ \partial_r \psi^* (\mathbf{r}) \right\} e^{-\alpha r} r^{-n-1} Y_l^{m*} (\theta ,\varphi )\right]\cdot\hat{n}dA .
\end{equation}

This simplifies as follows using spherical coordinates \((r, \theta, \varphi)\):
\begin{align*}
&\lim _{\varepsilon \rightarrow 0^{+}} \iint _{S_{\varepsilon}} \left\{\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r}) \left[- n r^{-n-2}-\alpha r^{-n-1}+\mathcal{O}(r^{-n+1})\right]+ \left.\partial_{r} \psi^{*}(\mathbf{r})\right|_{r=\varepsilon} \left[r^{-n-1}+\mathcal{O}(r^{-n+1})\right]\right\}\\
&=4 \pi \left[n |\psi(0)|^{2}-i\alpha \langle \hat{p}_{r}\rangle\right].
\end{align*}

Now consider the right hand side of our original integral expression which involves the potential term:
\begin{align*}
\int d\mathbf{r}&\,\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r}) V(\mathbf{r}) r^{-n-1} e^{-\alpha r} Y_{l}^{m*}(\theta,\varphi)
\\
&=-\frac{i}{2m} \int d\mathbf{r} \,\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r}) \left[e^{-\alpha r} r^{-n-1} \left(Y_{l}^{m*}(\theta,\varphi)\right)^{T} \times \boldsymbol{\sigma} \cdot \mathbf{k}\right]
\\
&=-i \int d\mathbf{r} \,\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r}) \left[e^{-\alpha r} r^{-n-1} \left(Y_{l}^{m*}(\theta,\varphi)\right)^{T} \times \boldsymbol{\sigma} \cdot \mathbf{k}\right],
\end{align*}

where $\mathbf{k}$ is the unit vector along the z-axis.

Combining these results together gives us:
\begin{align*}
4 \pi &\left(n |\psi(0)|^{2}- i \alpha \langle p_{r}\rangle\right)= E \int d\mathbf{r} \,\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r}) r^{-n-1} e^{-\alpha r} Y_{l}^{m*}(\theta,\varphi)-\int d\mathbf{r} \,\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r}) V(\mathbf{r}) r^{-n-1} e^{-\alpha r} Y_{l}^{m*}(\theta,\varphi),
\end{align*}

which can be rewritten as:
\begin{align*}
4 \pi n |\psi(0)|^{2}=&-i \alpha \langle p_{r}\rangle+\int d\mathbf{r} \,\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r}) \left(V(\mathbf{r})-E\right) r^{-n-1} e^{-\alpha r} Y_{l}^{m*}(\theta,\varphi)+\\& +\int d\mathbf{r} \,\psi^{*}(\mathbf{r}) \left(-i \alpha r^{-n-1} e^{-\alpha r} Y_{l}^{m*}(\theta,\varphi)+\frac{l(l+1)}{\sqrt{2mr^{5}}}\right).
\end{align*}

Taking the limit as $\alpha$ approaches zero yields:
\begin{align*}
4 \pi n |\psi(0)|^{2}=-\left\langle\frac{V'}{r}\right\rangle+\frac{(l+1)(l+2)}{2m}.
\end{align*}

Finally setting $n=1$, we obtain the desired result:
\[\boxed{| \psi(0) |^2 =\frac{m}{2 \pi}\left\langle\frac{\mathrm{d} V}{\mathrm{d} r}\right\rangle-\frac{1}{2 \pi}\left\langle\frac{L^{2}}{r^{3}}\right\rangle}.
